                  Cthulhu for kids.  What will they think of next? <br />
<br />
Love the &quot;D is for Dagon, because he's one of the gods, not one of the deep ones who are one step up from frogs.&quot;<br />
<br />
<a href="http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=145109" target="_blank">http://forum.newsarama.com/showthread.php?t=145109</a><br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				The book is Baby's First Mythos. It's published in the classic board book format you might remember from children's books of old, but its contents are something far different. It's goal – to teach your child the ABC's – Mythos style. Whether they’re a budding Wednesday Adams or not, Baby's First Mythos brings kids the alphabet, basic counting, and even nursery rhymes all in the vein of Clthulu. <br />
<br />
Aimed at kids, BFM also works as an all-ages affair for Lovecraft enthusiasts wanting to see a different side of the Mythos. Although it's not quite comics, it could (and does) easily sit side-by-side with Hellboy in your local comic store.<br />
<br />
Baby's First Mythos writer is C.J. Henderson, a fiction writer best known for his &quot;Teddy London&quot; supernatural detective series, which began with The Things That Are Not There. He also penned the Jack Hagee hardboiled private eye series and wrote non-fiction books such as The Encyclopedia of Science Fiction Movies and Black Sabbath: The Ozzy Osbourne Years.<br />
<br />
For more, we talked with the writer by email.<br />
<br />
Newsarama: Let's start from scratch, C.J. What's Baby's First Mythos about?<br />
<br />
C.J. Henderson: Simply put, it's an &quot;A to Z&quot; book for kids being raised by very strange parents. At least, the first edition was. When the book proved to be such a phenomenal (and truly surprising) hit in its original, chap-book form, it was suggested it go to hardback. I had always wanted it to be a real thick cover kid's book, and so I was all for that, but perfect-binding meant it had to have more pages. So, now you get a fancy-shmancy intro from Dr. Robert M. Price and afterward from Professor William J. Jones, the original alphabet, &quot;A is for Azathoth,&quot; &quot;I is for Innsmouth,&quot; and the such, and then a &quot;1 thru 0&quot; with each number surrounded by the correct amount of creatures, and lastly a nursery rhyme. <br />
<br />
NRAMA: What was the spark for this? The initial idea that led to the finished product? <br />
<br />
CJH: Here's the story. Years ago, doing horror conventions, I because aware of the vast amount of baby carriages being pushed around at conventions. I'd be at horror cons, with witches, skeletons, blood splattered porn stars, chainsaw-wielding psychos, werewolves, et cetera, all running around, and then these babies being pushed around through them. Sitting at my table, watching these moms expose their toddlers to all this horror, I started picking up the book New Mythos Legends, that sports a truly awesome horror on its cover by the legendary AllenK (if you don't know who I mean, go to <a href="http://www.AllenK.com" target="_blank">www.AllenK.com</a> and check him out!), and I would wave it at these moms and shout:<br />
<br />
&quot;Baby's First Mythos!&quot;<br />
<br />
This became a running gag. Okay, so one time I'm at this really, really terrible convention. Two of the other author guests (Jaunty John French and Jumpin' James Chambers) and a publisher guest (Smokin' Vince Sneed) were sitting at my table with me, waiting for me to give up and leave with them. A baby carriage goes by and I shout &quot;Baby's First Mythos,&quot; and the three of them start to howl. So, I say, innocently, &quot;Jeez, I'm going to have to write that book some day,&quot; and Vince says, &quot;Yes--for me!&quot;<br />
<br />
So at first, I don't want to do the book because, idiot that I am, I think this is going to ruin my reputation as a mythos writer. You know, that folks will think I'm just one of these anything-for-a-buck hacks that will turn Lovecraft's work inside-out with no consideration outside of scraping up more pennies. Believe me, there's enough of those morons. But, Vince keeps hammering at me to do it, and James and John are completely on his side. Everyone is egging me on to do the book, so anyway, I get an idea.<br />
<br />
Now understand, Vince has already used my daughter's work for his sell-out zombie anthology, The Dead Walk. I know he likes her work. So, I say, &quot;okay, I'll do it, but only if Erica does the artwork.&quot; Vince agrees on the spot and I'm chuckling inside because I know she simply has too much work to do to take on the project. I know she can't do it. So then, I get home from the con, tell her the whole story, and she says, &quot;Sure, that'd be cool.&quot;<br />
<br />
Which means, I trapped myself into doing this book I thought would ruin my career. Luckily, the whole world seems to have embraced the book, so it all turned out all right, and I even got over myself, which was almost as good as being able to hand my wife royalty checks.<br />
<br />
Of course, I should probably add a note for those who know the book was published by Z-Man Games and not Vince Sneed's Die, Monster, Die. Vince fully intended to do the book. But, I ran into Zev, owner of Z-Man, at a Barnes &amp; Noble appearance we were both doing to promote a show, and when I found out he was a Lovecraft fan, I showed him the advance proofs. He got in touch with Vince, wanting to get copies to sell, and wound up buying Vince out. So, I got the terrific Sneed layouts for which he is rightly famous, and Zev's more extensive distribution system. It was just a project blessed from day one by mighty Cthulhu, and I for one am a happy guy.<br />
<br />
NRAMA: That's a great story. This book is great for two audiences – a fun interpretation for people aware of Lovecraft, and a humorous introduction for those who have not. When you were creating this, did you have an audience in mind? Also, what's the reception been like from readers?<br />
<br />
CJH: No, no audience in mind. In fact, I was so mad at myself for getting myself &quot;stuck&quot; doing the book, I just dashed all the poetry off for the original chap-book in just one night. Remember, I didn't think anyone would want the book, that I was an idiot for getting involved, and that no one would want one. But then, I'm one of those insecure writers who thinks no one is ever going to want anything I do. On the other hand, the reception has been over-whelming. Thousands and thousands of copies have been sold to people buying them as shower presents, as well as for their own kids. They buy one for the kid and one for their shelves. I think Erica's artwork has a lot more to do with that than me, but then, I'm the bloody genius who insisted on having her art (see, writers get to rewrite history as well as their stories), so I guess I deserve all the credit anyway. Right?<br />
<br />
Seriously, I've been very touched by the reaction of the hundreds and hundreds of Baby's First Mythos owners I've met over the past few years. People really love the book, and they've made me very happy I wrote it. And, to all the critics who have bad-mouthed my one nite poetry session while praising Erica's artwork, all I have to say is, well, of course the meter and rhyme schemes are off ... to your ear. It's poetry not meant to be read by human tongue.<br />
<br />
Sheessshhhhh!<br />
<br />
NRAMA: Along those lines, how hard was it to find something to rhyme with 'Trapezohedron '?<br />
<br />
CJH: Just as hard as you can imagine.<br />
<br />
Baby’s First Mythos can be found at bookstores and online booksellers.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
                  
		</div>
